A few weeks ago I refactored my application to use a custom error handler instead of handling errors in the routes.

I added this below all my routers.
```
app.use(function(err,req,res,next) {
    console.log(err)
    if (res.headersSent === false) {
        res.sendStatus(400)
    }
   next(err)
})
```

It allows me to use next(err) in my routes and if a response hasn't been sent yet, return a 400 status code.

```
app.post("/do-something", function(req,res,next) {

    doSomething.test().then(() => {
        return res.sendStatus(200)
    }).catch((err) => {
        return next(err)
    })

 })
```

This all worked great when I initially tested it and is currently working in production.  However I am getting some odd behavior in development now.

Anytime that custom error handler is used I get a `net::ERR_SPDY_PROTOCOL_ERROR 400`  in the chrome console with an empty response (empty response breaks my app).

However, sending a 400 status code within the route itself works fine.

```
app.post("/do-something", function(req,res,next) {

    doSomething.test().then(() => {
        return res.sendStatus(200)
    }).catch((err) => {
        return res.sendStatus(400)
    })

 })
```

Removing the next(err) from the custom error handler also fixes the problem. 

```
app.use(function(err,req,res,next) {
    console.log(err)
    if (res.headersSent === false) {
        res.sendStatus(400)
    }
})
```

I can't find much info on what could be causing this.... I have tried on 2 different machines.  Please let me know if more details are needed. I am happy to add the response from chrome, etc. 

Thanks!

